                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d394">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.CC/6–2944: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-06-29T12:00:00+03:00"
                            >June 29, 1944—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 8:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2328. Your 1570, June 27, 9 p.m.<note n="92" xml:id="d394fn92">Not printed;
                        Secretary Hull instructed Ambassador Harriman to endeavor “to expedite the
                        Soviet reply and telegraph urgently” (500.CC/6–2744).</note> I sent a secret
                    and urgent letter to Molotov on June 28 inquiring when we may expect the Soviet
                    reply to the invitation to participate in a preliminary exchange of views on an
                    international security organization. I emphasized that my Government was most
                    anxious to have the acceptance of the Soviet Government as soon as possible.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
